A heat wave claimed 16 lives over the last four  days in Punjab province, reports and hospital sources said Thursday.
The sunstroke fatalities were reported from different places in the  southern and central parts of the province where temperatures ranged between  40 and 45 degrees Celsius.
Meanwhile, drought has left the Pakistani capital facing a water crisis  with the city's main Simly Dam reservoir suffering a sharp fall in water  levels.        The Islamabad administration would start water rationing for  the 300,000 city inhabitants during the current week, reports said.
